UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1046
1 AN ACT relating to postsecondary tuition waivers.
2 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
3 Section 1. KRS 164.515 is amended to read as follows:
4 (1) The spouse, regardless of age, and any child, stepchild, or orphan, under the age of
5 twenty-six (26), of a permanently and totally disabled member of the Kentucky
6 National Guard or Reserve Component injured while on state active duty, active
7 duty for training, or inactive duty training, or a permanently and totally disabled
8 war veteran, or a one hundred percent (100%) service-connected disabled veteran
9 regardless of wartime service, or prisoner of war or member of the Armed Services
10 declared missing in action shall not be required to pay any matriculation or tuition
11 fees upon his admission to any state-supported institution of higher education or to
12 any state-supported vocational training school for a period not in excess of forty-
13 five (45) months in order to obtain a diploma, nor in excess of the lesser number of
14 months required for a certificate of completion.
15 (2) To be entitled to benefits under this section the parent or stepparent of the child
16 claiming benefits if living must be rated permanently and totally disabled for
17 pension purposes or one hundred percent (100%) disabled for compensation
18 purposes by the United States Department of Veterans Affairs or the Department of
19 Defense. If the veteran is deceased, the claim to benefits is to be based on the rating
20 held by the veteran at the time of death or if a prisoner of war or missing in action,
21 must have been declared as such by the Department of Defense. Members of the
22 Kentucky National Guard must be rated permanently and totally disabled as
23 provided in KRS Chapter 342. The parent's, stepparent's, or spouse's service and
24 rating must be evidenced by certification from the records of the Kentucky
25 Department of Military Affairs, United States Department of Veterans Affairs, or
26 the Department of Defense of the United States.
27 (3) The parent-child relationship must be shown by birth certificate, legal adoption
Page 1 of 17
XXXX 1/23/2026 1:45 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1046
1 papers, marriage certificate, or other documentary evidence. A stepchild must be a
2 member of the veteran's household. The spousal relationship must be shown by a
3 marriage certificate or other documentary evidence.
4 (4) To entitle a spouse, child, stepchild, or orphan to benefit under this section the
5 disabled member of the National Guard or Reserve Component veteran living or
6 deceased must have served on state active duty, active duty for training, or inactive
7 duty training or active duty with the Armed Forces of the United States, and his
8 discharge must have been under honorable conditions. He must be a resident or, if
9 deceased, have been a resident of the Commonwealth of Kentucky.
10 (5) No provision of this section shall serve to deny these benefits to an eligible spouse,
11 child, stepchild, or orphan, who enlists, or who fulfills a military obligation, in the
12 Armed Forces of the United States and is discharged under honorable conditions;
13 the period of time spent in the military service to be compensated by like time,
14 beyond the age of twenty-six (26) years if required, but not in excess of the period
15 of enrollment as set forth in subsection (1) of this section.
16 (6) The marriage of an eligible child, stepchild, or orphan, shall not serve to deny full
17 entitlement to the benefits provided in this section.
18 (7) The student shall complete the Free Application for Federal Student Aid to
19 determine the level of need and eligibility for state and federal financial aid
20 programs. The amount of tuition waived under this section shall not exceed the
21 cost of tuition and mandatory fees at the institution less any state or federal
22 grants received, which shall be credited first to the student's tuition and fees.
23 Section 2. KRS 164.2841 is amended to read as follows:
24 (1) (a) Any person whose parent or any nonmarried widow or widower whose spouse
25 was a resident of the Commonwealth of Kentucky upon becoming a law
26 enforcement officer, firefighter, or volunteer firefighter and who was killed
27 while in active service or training for active service or who died as a result of
